ONEOK FIELD SERVICES COMPANY, L.L.C. Statement of Operating Conditions Section 311 Transportation Services ARTICLE I AVAILABILITY 1.1 ONEOK Field Services Company, L.L.C. (Company) will transport Gas pursuant to Section 311(A)(2) of the Natural Gas Policy Act of 1978, as amended (Act), on a firm or interruptible basis for any person and/or entity desiring to transport Gas on Company's Pipeline System (as defined herein) pursuant to the terms and conditions hereof (each such person or entity and all affiliates of each such person or entity hereafter jointly referred to as a Shipper) provided: (a) Capacity is available in the Company's jurisdictional Pipeline System from time to time; (b) Shipper has executed an agreement for the transportation of gas (hereinafter referred to as the Service Agreement) or an extension thereof with the Company; (c) Such transportation service is performed "on behalf of" an interstate pipeline or a local distribution company served by an interstate pipeline company within the terms of Section 311 of the Act and the rules and regulations thereunder. If the qualified status of the proposed transaction is in doubt, then Shipper must apply for and receive a final, non-appealable declaratory order from the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) or a successor agency thereto, affirming the qualifying status of the transaction prior to the commencement of transportation services by Company; (d) Shipper, Company and third-party transporter (including Company's affiliates) have obtained, as appropriate, or will obtain reasonably in advance of the commencement of service, unless waived by Company, all State and Federal approvals for services to be provided by Shipper, Company and third-party transporter (including Company's affiliates) related to those rendered by Company, including services that are necessary for said Gas to be received into and delivered from Company's facilities; (e) Gas is physically delivered to Company's Pipeline System; (f) Company, unless otherwise agreed, is not required to construct, modify, expand, or acquire any facilities. Company shall agree or not agree to construct, modify, expand, or organize any such facilities on a nondiscriminatory basis; and (g) Each person or entity and all affiliates thereof shall be considered as one Shipper for all purposes hereunder. ARTICLE II REQUESTS FOR SERVICE 2.1 Company will accept requests from Shippers for firm or interruptible transportation service, subject to the availability of interruptible capacity within Company's Pipeline System for the provision of such service. Company's Pipeline System is located downstream of the Company's gas processing plants as shown on maps on file with the Company. Company's facilities upstream of the processing plants are classified as gathering facilities. Upon Company's acceptance of a request and Shipper's satisfaction of Company's credit requirements, Company and Shipper shall enter into a Service Agreement for firm or interruptible transportation service. The Service Agreement may also include provisions for the gathering of such gas, if such services are desired by Shipper. Such contract(s) shall be at least one month in duration and shall provide that transportation service shall begin and terminate on dates mutually agreed to by Shipper and Company. 2.2 If Shipper does not execute a Service Agreement for transportation service within thirty (30) days of the date on which Company tenders such contract to Shipper, Shipper's request for service may be null and void. ARTICLE III APPLICABILITY AND CHARACTER OF SERVICE 3.1 This Operating Statement shall apply to all firm and interruptible transportation service rendered under Service Agreements on the Pipeline System pursuant to Section 311(a)(2) of the Act and Section 284.123 (b)(2) of the Commission's Regulations. 3.2 When Shipper has contracted for transportation service and capacity is available within Company's Pipeline System for the provision of such service, to the extent capacity is available therefor, Company shall receive from Shipper, or for the account of shipper, the quantity scheduled pursuant to the Service Agreement. To the extent that capacity is available within Company's Pipeline System, Company shall transport and make available to or on behalf of Shipper such capacity adjusted for any fuel and use quantity as set forth in the Statement of Current Effective Rates. 3.3 Company shall render service under this Operating Statement and the Service Agreement under Subpart C of Part 284 of the FERC's Regulations. 3.4 Subject to the terms herein, and with respect to firm transportation service, Company agrees to accept on each day at each point(s) of receipt designated in the Service Agreement, a quantity of gas provided in such Service Agreement and which shall be referred to as the “Maximum Daily Quantity” or “MDQ.” Company may accept or refuse quantities of gas tendered on any day by Shipper which are in excess of the MDQ. Any excess gas so accepted by the Company will be subject to all the terms and provisions herein. Commencing on the date Shipper initiates deliveries of gas to Company for transportation under the Service Agreement, Company will deliver an equivalent quantity to Shipper at the point(s) of delivery. 3.5 It shall be the responsibility of the Shipper to make all arrangements for the transportation of gas to be delivered into or received from the Pipeline System. The execution of a Service Agreement for transportation service in no way confers or implies any right on the part of Shipper to transportation service on upstream or downstream transport or gathering system(s) unless otherwise provided for in the agreement. 3.6 All nominations, scheduling, transportation, and priorities for service shall be subject to demands, priorities, requests and/or constraints made or imposed by upstream and/or downstream gatherers or transporters of Gas. ARTICLE IV SERVICE INTERRUPTION AND PRIORITY OF SERVICE 4.1 Company reserves the right to issue an operational flow order to alleviate conditions that threaten the safe operations or system integrity of the Company’s system or to maintain operations required to provide efficient and reliable service. 4.2 Curtailment and interruption of service may be ordered by the Company at any time if, in Company’s reasonable judgment, capacity or operating conditions so require, such as an event of force majeure, or it is desirable or necessary to make modifications, repairs or operating changes, the conduct of which will occasion interruptions, upon such notice as is reasonable under the circumstances. 4.3 If, for whatever reason, Company is unable to transport all quantities of gas nominated by Shipper under the Service Agreement, Company shall interrupt service thereunder in whole or in part on all or such portions of Company's system as may be necessary to be exercised on a not unduly discriminatory basis; provided, however, that Company will act as a reasonably prudent pipeline, subject to operating necessities to interrupt service (on that portion or portions of its system where such interruption is required) in the following order: (a) Interruptible transportation service (b) Firm transportation service. 4.4 Within each of the categories above, interruption shall be administered as described below. (a) Interruption of interruptible transportation service shall be administered so that service under the lowest economic value contract is interrupted first and service under the highest economic value contract is interrupted last. Where the same economic value or the same contract rate for service exists between Shippers’ service, interruption of that service shall be administered on a pro rata basis. (b) Interruption of firm transportation service shall be administered on a pro rata basis. 4.5 The Company and Shipper agree that in no event shall an interruption of service pursuant to this Article constitute a breach of the Service Agreement, and that Company shall not be liable to Shipper in damages or otherwise due to any such interruption of service. ARTICLE V DETERMINATION OF RECEIPT AND DELIVERY QUANTITIES, OPERATING COORDINATION AND ADJUSTMENTS 5.1 Gas received by Company for Shipper's account may be commingled with Gas received for other Shippers, and Gas delivered by Company for Shipper may be commingled with Gas delivered for other Shippers. Accordingly, the Gas delivered for Shipper and delivered to downstream transporters, may not be the same molecules as those received from Shipper hereunder. 5.2 Company and Shipper recognize that imbalances may occur between receipts and deliveries and on a daily, weekly, and monthly basis shall use commercially reasonable efforts to minimize imbalances. ARTICLE VI RATES 6.1 The applicable rate for transportation (not including gathering) service, shall be at the maximum rate allowed by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission for such service unless a discounted rate is agreed to by the parties. 6.2 As payment for service hereunder, Shipper shall pay the Company an amount equal to the charges set forth in the Service Agreement and the fees and charges described in the attachments thereto. Company shall retain an amount of Gas equal to any fuel and use quantity set forth in the Statement of Current Effective Rates. ARTICLE VII OTHER CHARGES 7.1 The following additional fees and charges also may be charged by Company to the extent applicable to the specific services provided hereunder: a) Shipper shall pay all applicable surcharges, fees, taxes, charges, and assessments, as set forth or discussed on the Statement of Current Effective Rates, imposed by or on behalf of any governmental entity in connection with the Service Agreement or in connection with the purchase, transportation and disposition of gas by or on behalf of Shipper pursuant to the Service Agreement including, but not limited to, municipal and/or supplemental fees, franchise fees and any supplements thereto and taxes; provided that Company shall pay all ad valorem taxes and assessments levied on the system and all appurtenant facilities. At the request of Company, Shipper will furnish Company with any information available to Shipper in connection with Company’s obligation under this article.; b) For the costs of all facilities which Company acquires, constructs, installs, modifies or rearrange to provide service hereunder specifically applicable to such Shipper, and which Shipper has agreed to reimburse Company in whole or in part. Company will require reimbursement on a nondiscriminatory basis; c) Unless otherwise provided, all substances whether or not of commercial value, including all liquid and liquefiable hydrocarbons of whatever nature, that Company recovers in the course of transporting the quantities of natural Gas tendered hereunder by or on behalf of Shipper shall be Company's sole property, and Company shall not be obligated to account for, or pay to Shipper for, any value, whether or not realized by Company, that may attach or be said to attach to such substances; d) Shipper shall reimburse Company for: (1) any natural Gas severance or sales tax, first use tax, gross receipt tax, or taxes similar in nature, or equivalent in effect, which are now or hereafter imposed or assessed against Company by any lawful authority as a result of the transportation of natural Gas; and (2) for any charges which the Company incurs from other parties in rendering service for Shipper which charges are related to the transportation service rendered to Shipper pursuant to this Operating Statement. e) Shipper shall be responsible for and shall bear any penalties imposed by upstream or downstream gatherers or transporters assessed by such upstream or downstream gatherers or transporters for imbalances in receipts and deliveries. Shipper shall defend and hold Company harmless from all such payments or charges for imbalances. Any reimbursement due Company by Shipper pursuant to this Article VI shall be due and payable to Company within ten (10) days of receipt by Shipper of Company's invoice(s) for same. ARTICLE VIII RESERVATIONS 8.1 Company reserves the unilateral right from time to time to make any changes to, or to supersede, or to cancel the rates, charges and any and all terms and conditions stated in this Operating Statement and the applicability thereof, the Service Agreement and any other provisions relating to Company's interruptible transportation service, subject to the provisions of the Act and the FERC's Regulations thereunder and the Service Agreement. ARTICLE IX TERMINATION 9.1 For each Service Agreement Company's obligation to provide service, and Shipper's contractual and other rights, to receive such service shall terminate on the earlier of the date provided in the applicable Service Agreement for the termination of said service, the date on which Company determines on a nondiscriminatory basis to cease transporting Gas pursuant to Section 311(a)(2) of the Act or the date provided for in this Operating Statement. The Service Agreement may be terminated or extended on terms mutually agreed to by Shipper and Company, if the FERC, by final order not subject to appeal, determines this Operating Statement is not in accordance with the applicable FERC regulations or governing statutes, or is not fair and equitable to all parties. Shipper shall pay for all services rendered prior to such termination. ARTICLE X SERVICE AGREEMENT 10.1 Shipper shall enter into a contract with Company in the form of a Service Agreement which may be filed with the FERC. The executed Service Agreement, together with all attachments, Exhibits and Schedules attached thereto and the Operating Statement as they may be amended in the future, shall constitute the entire agreement between the parties for Gas transportation service. ARTICLE XI QUALITY 11.1 The gas received and delivered under the terms of the Service Agreement shall meet downstream gas quality requirements. If Shipper’s gas fails to meet the gas quality specifications of a downstream interconnecting pipeline so that the downstream interconnecting pipeline refuses or provides notice that it will refuse to accept gas from Company and such refusal impacts Company’s system, the Company, it is reasonable discretion, may reject a nomination or curtail Shipper’s deliveries to Company until the gas quality issues have been resolved. Notwithstanding the foregoing, neither Shipper nor Company shall be liable for receipt or delivery of non-conforming gas. Acceptance by Company of non-conforming gas at any point of receipt does not constitute waiver of this section 11.1 with respect to such gas, any other gas delivered under a Service Agreement in the future, or any claim for damages due to such failure to conform. ARTICLE XII CREDITWORTHINESS OF SHIPPER 12.1 For existing facilities, Company shall not be required to initiate Service on behalf of any Shipper or provide Service or to continue Service for any Shipper who is or has become insolvent or who, at Company’s request, fails within a commercially reasonable time to demonstrate creditworthiness as determined by the Company in its reasonable discretion; provided, however, Shipper may receive Service if Shipper furnishes good and sufficient security as determined by Company in its reasonable discretion. Unless otherwise agreed to in a Service Agreement, if Company has reasonable grounds for insecurity regarding the ability of Shipper to perform its obligations, Company shall require Adequate Assurance of Performance. “Adequate Assurance of Performance” shall mean sufficient security in a form, amount, for a term and from an issuer all as reasonably acceptable to Company, including cash, prepayment, a standby irrevocable letter of credit or a guaranty. Upon Company’s request for Adequate Assurance of Performance, Shipper shall have three (3) business days to provide such Adequate Assurance of Performance as described above. If Shipper fails to provide the requested Adequate Assurance of Performance within such three (3) business day period, then Company may suspend Services to Shipper upon providing an additional three (3) business days’ notice. For the purpose of this article, the insolvency of a Shipper shall be evidenced by the filing by Shipper, or any parent entity thereof, of a voluntary petition in bankruptcy or the entry of a decree or order by a court having jurisdiction over the premises adjudging Shipper bankrupt or insolvent or approving, as properly filed, a petition seeking reorganization, arrangement, adjustment or composition or in respect of the Shipper under the Federal Bankruptcy Act or any other applicable federal or state law or appointing a receiver, liquidator, assignee, trustee, sequestrator (or other similar official) of the Shipper or of any substantial part of its property or the ordering of the winding-up or liquidation of its affairs, with said order or decree continuing unstayed and in effect for a period of sixty (60) consecutive days. 12.2 In the event that Company agrees to construct new facilities or to expand or extend its existing facilities, Company may require additional Adequate Assurance of Performance in a form, amount, for a term and from an issuer all as reasonably acceptable to Company and as agreed to by the parties in a Service Agreement. ARTICLE XIII FORCE MAJEURE 13.1 In the event either party is rendered unable wholly or in part by force majeure to carry out its obligations under the Agreement, other than to make payments due there under, it is agreed that on such party giving notice and full particulars of such force majeure in writing to the other party as soon as possible after the occurrence of the cause relied on, then the obligations of the noticing party, so far as they are affected by such force majeure, shall be suspended during the continuance of any inability so caused but for no longer period, and such cause shall as far as possible be remedied with all reasonable dispatch. 13.2 The term “force majeure” as employed herein shall include acts of God, strikes, lockouts or other industrial disturbances, acts of the public enemy, sabotage, wars, blockades, insurrections, riots, epidemics, landslides, lightning, earthquakes, fires, storms, floods, high water, washouts or other natural disasters, threat of physical harm or damage resulting in the evacuation or shut down of facilities necessary for the production or delivery or receipt or use of gas, arrests and restraints of governments and people, civil disturbances, explosions, breakage or accident to machinery or lines of pipe or facilities in which the gas is used, the necessity for unscheduled testing or for making unplanned repairs or alterations to wells, machinery, facilities or lines of pipe through which the gas is moved, or freezing of wells or lines of pipe or facilities through which the gas is moved or in which the gas is used, partial or entire failure of wells, processing, gathering or transportation facilities or gasification and gas manufacturing facilities or facilities in which the gas is used, the orders of any court or governmental authority or agency having or asserting jurisdiction or the refusal or withdrawal of any necessary order, certificate or permit by any court or governmental authority or agency having or asserting jurisdiction, any acts or omissions (including, without limitation, failure to take, transport or deliver gas) of a transporter of gas to or for Company or Shipper, and any other causes, whether of the kind herein enumerated or otherwise, not reasonably within the control of the party claiming suspension and which by the exercise of due diligence such party is unable to prevent or overcome. Such term shall likewise include, (a) in those instances where either party is required to obtain servitudes, rights-of way grants, permits, certificates or licenses to enable such party to fulfill its obligations under the Agreement, the inability of such party to acquire or the delays on the part of such party in acquiring, at reasonable cost and after the exercise of reasonable diligence, such servitudes, rights-of-way grants, permits or certificates or licenses, and (b) in those instances where either party is required to furnish materials and supplies for the purpose of constructing or maintaining facilities or is required to secure permits or permissions from any governmental agency to enable such party to fulfill its obligations under the Agreement, the inability of such party to acquire or the delays on the part of such party in acquiring, at reasonable cost and after the exercise of reasonable diligence, such materials and supplies, permits and permissions. 13.3 The parties agree that the settlement of strikes or lockouts shall be entirely within the discretion of the party having the difficulty and that the above requirement that any force majeure shall be remedied with all reasonable dispatch shall not require the settlement of strikes or lockouts by acceding to the demands of the opposing person when such course is inadvisable in the discretion of the party having the difficulty.
